\description{
Performs the Burden test using optimal weights derived from the GLOW framework.
The Burden test combines Z-scores linearly and is most powerful when all causal
variants have effects in the same direction (all positive or all negative).

The test statistic is:
\deqn{S_{Burden} = \sum_{i=1}^{m} w_i Z_i}

where \eqn{w_i} are optimal weights and \eqn{Z_i} are marginal score Z-scores.

\strong{CRITICAL}: The Burden test statistic is a LINEAR combination of Z-scores.
Under the null hypothesis, S follows a normal distribution with variance
\eqn{\sigma^2 = w^T M w}, where M is the correlation matrix of Z-scores.
The p-value is calculated using the normal distribution (NOT Davies method,
NOT chi-square distribution).
}
\details{
\strong{Algorithm}:
\enumerate{
\item Compute scaled effect sizes: \eqn{B^* = \sqrt{diag(M_s)} \times B / s_0}
\item Calculate optimal weights using Optimal_Weights_M with:
\itemize{
\item Transformation g(x) = x (identity function)
\item Degrees of freedom df = Inf (indicates Burden test)
\item Effect size estimates B*
\item Variant-importance scores PI
\item Correlation matrix M
}
\item Construct weight matrix with optimal weights (BE, APE) and equal weights
\item Call omni_SgZ_test which routes to burden_test for each weight scheme
\item burden_test uses normal distribution: \eqn{p = 2 \Phi(-|S|/\sigma)}
}

\strong{Optimal Weight Schemes}:
\itemize{
\item \strong{wts_BE} (Best Estimator): Optimal under normal approximation assuming
random effect sizes \eqn{\theta_i \sim PI_i \delta_{B_i} + (1-PI_i) \delta_0}
\item \strong{wts_APE} (Asymptotically Powerful Estimator): Accounts for correlation
and variance structure, optimal for sparse signals
\item \strong{wts_equ}: Equal weights baseline (simple sum of Z-scores)
}

The final Burden p-value is the minimum of the equal weights p-value (last row).

\strong{When Burden Test is Optimal}:
\itemize{
\item All causal variants have effect in the same direction
\item Effect sizes are relatively homogeneous
\item Strong directional hypothesis (e.g., all deleterious or all protective)
}

\strong{P-value Calculation} (MANDATORY - DO NOT MODIFY):
The p-value is computed using the normal distribution:
\deqn{p = 2 \times P(N(0, \sigma^2) > |S|) = 2 \times \Phi(-|S|/\sigma)}
where \eqn{\sigma^2 = w^T M w} is the variance of S under the null.

This is NOT a quadratic form - it is a linear combination. The statistic S
is NOT squared. The Davies method is NOT used. The chi-square distribution
is NOT used.

\strong{Computational Complexity}: O(m^2) for weight calculation and p-value

\strong{Assumptions}:
\itemize{
\item Z-scores are standard normal under null hypothesis
\item M is the correlation matrix of Z-scores
\item Effect sizes B are on the standardized scale
